Jonson called Gervase Markham 'a scoundrel' while
others have called Markham a 'bad poet.' The verdict
of history should be that Markham was a scoundrel
who wrote bad poetry. The verdict of history is j
ust the reverse.

As the shareholder of a boys' theatre company
Markham wrote lewd pedophilic plays, for some years
near-fatally feuded with Gervase Holland and otherwise
disrupted society, but in another persona, apparently,
Markham published engagingly empirical books on
practical husbandry, horse training, military exercises
and Bacon's favorite subject, beer-making.

Computers find Markham's books the closest match to
Shakespeare's style of any Elizabethan author including
Marlowe.

Markham wrote the following encomium or mock encomium
(which is neither engaging nor empirical) to the Veres.
I say 'mock encomium' because hyperbole and amplificatio
distinguishes the mock encomium from the encomium.

Markham's suggestion that the Vere line extends back
to the 'first hour of Caesar' is more hyperbolic than
anything in the Gratulationes Valdinenses, Harvey's mock
encomium to Oxford or in 'To the Memory of My Beloved,'
Jonson's mock encomium to the actor.

