----------------------------------------------------
&lt;&lt;A fractal is a rough or fragmented geometric shape that can be subdivided
in parts, each of which is (at least approximately) a smaller copy of the
whole. Fractals are generally self-similar (bits look like the whole) and
independent of scale (they look similar, no matter how close you zoom in).
Many mathematical structures are fractals; e.g. Sierpinski triangle, Koch
snowflake, Peano curve, Mandelbrot set and Lorenz attractor. Fractals also
describe many real-world objects that do not have simple geometric shapes,
such as clouds, mountains, turbulence, and coastlines. Benoit Mandelbrot,
the discoverer of the Mandelbrot set, coined the term &quot;fractal&quot; in 1975 from
the Latin fractus or &quot;to break&quot;. He defines a fractal as a set for which the
Hausdorff Besicovich dimension strictly exceeds the topological dimension.
However, he is not satisfied with this definition as it excludes sets one
would consider fractals.&gt;&gt;
