There are other associations with GOLE~ and 'gool' indicating a whirl pool.

Than syr Gawaine the gude a galaye he takys
And glides up at a gole with gud mens or armes.
/Morte Arthure, MS Lincoln, f. 92

The stems gol~ and gold~ are A. Sax., and commonly attributed to plants and
insects, used as verb, noun and adjective. GOLD-HEWEN; of a golden colour
[A. Sax].

I was trying to find an early use of GHO`ST, which is an unusual formation
of stem letters, and it appears to be [Shak.]

GUIE~ means to guide [Fairfax], while GUILERY means deceit [Derby]. GULDE
means gold [Ritson] and a GUIMAD is a fish mentioned by Skinner as caught in
the river Dee. Of course GUINIVER also has watery associations, or rather
her asssociates had, as Launcelot du Lake, eg. Famous for her gallantries,
the term 'a guiniver' was applied to any such 'flighty' woman.

GULL: (1) a dupe or fool. Very common in the old dramatists. (3) To sweep
away by the force of running water.

GULLE: Gay, fine; [A. Sax] ~gyl?
The Jewes alle of that gate
Wex all fulle gulle and grene.
