Damn! Although it's obviously not surprising, a-priori, that it should
have been done that year, I was hoping the interval to have been longer.

I've been preparing the text, on spec. Current editions are a little
sloppy, and all omit Dunlap's 40 pages of back matter, which has plunged
me into a nightmare of footnotes on footnotes, and altogether too much
of the verse of Anna &quot;The Swan of Lichfield&quot; Seward (which Scott called
mostly &quot;execrable&quot;).

(On the other hand, it has led me by chance to discover &quot;History of
Amelia, or Malevolence Defeated&quot;, a positively magnificent illustration
of why Jane Austen is a great novelist and other people aren't, which I
have preserved for the digital age at
&lt;URL:&gt;.)

I quite like &quot;André&quot;. It takes a certain effort to put oneself into
sympathy with 18th-century tragedy, but, that once done, &quot;André&quot; seems
notable for its spareness. In its tight timeframe and avoidance of
physical action on stage, it seems almost Greek.

At the very least, you have to give Dunlap credit for sheer balls,
writing a tragedy about André when Washington was still alive (and had
only recently been a familiar sight in New York), and opening a play
about the American Revolution with an anti-war speech. And Dunlap's
pentameter is far more supple than the usual Frenchified thump of the age.

