substitutions.

To take the later first, what is 'literal' means 'of what is written' - and
so is 'the truth' in as much as we report what is written, but does not
imply an implicit veracity of the text in the comprehension of what it
reports:-

and there is often a conflation of terms such as mythological, which is not
synonymous with what is historical. History is an exoteric record of events.
A mythos is an esoteric record of consciousness.

A result is that a 'literal truth' which reports events as being
historically true (or otherwise) is not in fact any address to what is a
mythological truth.

This was the case with the Greeks and also Egyptians. If we attempt to
understand their records and artifacts only from an historical perspective
of outward events, I suggest that we miss the point of the initial record
which may have more to do with an intersection between what might be called
mythic space [or consciousness] and linear events [or history].

That is, between space and time.

